body:
## Steps to reproduce the issue

Given the following (a minimized circuit that was spit out by a compiler), try `read_verilog t.v`

```verilog
module t(.v(t$IO));
  inout  t$IO;
  wire t$IO;

  TriState #(.width(32'd1)) t(.I(1'b0), .OE(1'd0), .O(), .IO(t$IO));
endmodule

module TriState
    ( inout IO
    , output O
    , input OE
    , input I
    );
  assign IO = (OE) ? I : { width { 1'bz } };
  assign O  = IO;
endmodule
```

## Expected behavior

The `v` port for module `t` should point to the `t$IO` net; in effect something like:

```verilog
  assign v = t$IO;
```

More importantly, multiple aliases to the same net should be supported, as in the example from SO:

```verilog
module linked_io ( .io_A(io), .io_B(io), i, c );
  inout io;
  input i, c;
  assign io = c ? i : 1'bz;
endmodule
```

## Actual behavior

Yosys simply errors during parsing module `t`: `t.v:1: ERROR: syntax error, unexpected TOK_ID, expecting '.'`. This is actually a Verilog 2001 feature, apparently(!), which is intended to allow you to alias two ports to point to the same net. Apparently, this is one of the only ways to e.g. drive an `inout` from another `inout`. See https://stackoverflow.com/a/47293378 as well (some tools apparently support `tran` as well, for this case.)

For details, see IEEE-1364-2001 section 12.3.3 `Port declarations`.

## Workarounds

If you only need one IO connection to refer to that net, you can obviously use a `wire`. For multiple I/O aliases to the same net, there is no known workaround I am aware of?

